In Manitoba, an RHA is a regional governance structure set up by the provincial government to be responsible for the delivery and administration of health services in a specified geographic area. From July 2002 to 2 June 2012 Manitoba consisted for the following RHAs: Winnipeg, Brandon, South Eastman, Assiniboine, Central, Parkland, North Eastman, Interlake, Burntwood, NOR-MAN, and Churchill. On 1 June 2012 these existing 11 RHAs were amalgamated into five larger regions. The new RHAs are listed below, with the old RHAs listed in brackets:
Winnipeg (Winnipeg, Churchill);
Interlake-Eastern (Interake, North Eastman);
Prairie Mountain (Assiniboine, Brandon, Parkland);
Southern (Central, South Eastman);
Northern (Burntwood, NOR-MAN)
